  "signature": "ed25519:b2e3d4f5a6c7b8e9d0f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d1e2f3a4b5c6d7e8f9a0b1c2d3",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At MRL 5 for a Class III device, SQA must demonstrate formal version control, traceable build records, and independent code review. Gradation 4 requires documented test coverage reports and regression suite execution prior to each simulation campaign.",
      "rationale": "SQA activities include version-controlled repository with tagged releases and a regression test suite covering 87% of solver code paths. Independent peer review was conducted for the hemolysis sub-model. Achieved level 3 because formal independent code audit by a third party was not completed; internal review only was performed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 4 requires order-of-accuracy verification via the Method of Manufactured Solutions (MMS) for all governing equations active in the hemolysis simulation, including the power-law hemolysis transport equation. Results must confirm theoretical convergence rates within 5% tolerance.",
      "rationale": "MMS verification was performed for the Navier-Stokes solver and confirmed second-order spatial accuracy. However, MMS was not extended to the hemolysis damage accumulation transport equation, leaving a gap in code verification for the primary quantity of interest. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted using meshes of 2.1M, 6.8M, and 18.4M cells. Richardson extrapolation was applied to velocity and wall shear stress fields. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for hemolysis index was computed at 4.7% on the finest mesh, exceeding the target of 2%. Achieved level 3 because GCI on the hemolysis quantity of interest did not meet the sub-2% threshold required at Gradation 4 for MRL 5. The rationale for setting Gradation 4 as required derives from the high consequence of hemolysis under-prediction in a Class III VAD; however, the formal structured acceptance criterion document was not filed in the evidence dossier at the time of assessment."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires that experimental test conditions replicate at least three of the five target operating points (flow rate and rotational speed combinations) used in the COU, with documented measurement uncertainty on inlet flow and rotational speed.",
      "rationale": "Experimental validation was conducted at all five target operating points (2.5 L/min at 2500 RPM, 3.5 L/min at 3000 RPM, 4.5 L/min at 3500 RPM, 5.0 L/min at 3000 RPM, and 6.0 L/min at 2500 RPM). Inlet flow uncertainty ±0.05 L/min and speed uncertainty ±15 RPM were documented. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At Gradation 4, output comparison must include statistical comparison metrics (e.g., NRMSE, U95 validation uncertainty) across all operating points, with validation uncertainty propagated from both experimental and numerical sources. A quantitative validation metric threshold of NRMSE < 15% on hemolysis index is required.",
      "rationale": "Hemolysis index predictions were compared to experimental measurements at all five operating points. NRMSE on hemolysis index was 21.3%, exceeding the 15% threshold. Validation uncertainty was computed by combining experimental repeatability (n=5 runs per point) with numerical GCI. The comparison methodology is sound but the magnitude of discrepancy prevents achievement of Gradation 4. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 4 requires that the primary QoI (hemolysis index, HI) used in validation is the same scalar quantity used in the regulatory submission, computed by the same post-processing pathway, with traceability documented from simulation output to reported value.",
      "rationale": "The hemolysis index computed in validation simulations is identical to the regulatory submission QoI: normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) computed via the ASTM F1841 formula applied to CFD-predicted shear stress and exposure time fields. Traceability chain from raw CFD output through post-processing script to reported NIH is documented in the simulation plan. Achieved level 4 meets required level 4."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires that validation activities were conducted on a geometry that is the same device as the COU device or a device with documented geometric similarity ratio within 10%, operating in the same fluid regime (blood analog, hematocrit 35–45%).",
      "rationale": "Validation was performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump, which is the same geometry used in the COU simulations. Blood analog fluid (glycerin-water, viscosity matched to 40% hematocrit blood) was used in experiments. Geometric similarity is exact (ratio 1.0). Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence was monitored via residual norms for continuity, momentum, and hemolysis transport equations. Residuals were reduced by four orders of magnitude for flow equations but only two orders of magnitude for the hemolysis transport equation due to stiff source terms in high-shear regions near the impeller blade tips. Round-off error analysis was not performed. The required Gradation 4 demands documented round-off error bounding and demonstration that iterative errors are negligible relative to discretization errors; neither was formally established. Achieved level 2 reflects that iterative convergence monitoring was performed but incompletely, and no round-off analysis was conducted. The selection of Gradation 4 as the required level reflects MRL 5 guidance for Class III devices where solver errors in the primary QoI transport equation must be rigorously bounded."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires a documented simulation plan reviewed by a qualified independent analyst, including boundary condition specification, turbulence model selection rationale, and hemolysis model parameter sources, prior to execution of production simulations.",
      "rationale": "A simulation plan was prepared and reviewed internally by the lead analyst and one colleague. Independent external review was not conducted. Boundary conditions and turbulence model (SST k-omega) selection are documented with literature references. Hemolysis model constants (C=1.8e-6, alpha=0.765, beta=2.416) are sourced from Giersiepen et al. with traceability. Achieved level 2 because the review was not conducted by a qualified independent analyst external to the project team."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 4 requires that model form uncertainty for the hemolysis constitutive model is quantified by comparing predictions from at least two alternative hemolysis models (e.g., Giersiepen, Taskin, and Arora models) and that the spread in predictions is incorporated into the total uncertainty budget.",
      "rationale": "The power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen et al.) was used as the sole constitutive model. No alternative hemolysis model was evaluated for comparison. Model form uncertainty was acknowledged qualitatively in the uncertainty section but was not quantified. This represents a significant gap at MRL 5 for a Class III device where model form uncertainty in the hemolysis constitutive relationship is a dominant uncertainty source. Achieved level 2 because model form uncertainty was acknowledged but not quantified through multi-model comparison."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 4 requires that all model input parameters are assigned probability distributions with documented sources, and that a global sensitivity analysis (e.g., Sobol indices) identifies the top contributing inputs to hemolysis index uncertainty, with results used to prioritize uncertainty reduction activities.",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification was performed with 500 samples. Input parameters with assigned distributions include: inlet flow rate (normal, CV=2%), rotational speed (normal, CV=0.5%), blood viscosity (log-normal, CV=8%), and hemolysis model exponents alpha and beta (uniform ±10% of nominal). Global sensitivity analysis using Sobol indices was computed, identifying alpha and beta as dominant contributors (combined Sobol index 0.71). However, geometric uncertainty (impeller clearance, surface roughness) was not included in the UQ sweep. Achieved level 3 because geometric inputs were excluded from the uncertainty analysis, preventing full Gradation 4 compliance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires that experimental test samples (pump units) are drawn from a production-representative manufacturing lot, with geometric inspection confirming dimensional conformance to nominal CAD within specified tolerances, and that at least three independent pump units are tested.",
      "rationale": "Test samples were not formally assessed due to lack of access to manufacturing records for the FDA generic pump used in validation experiments. The pump units used in experiments were prototype units with unknown lot traceability. This factor is flagged as not-assessed and represents an epistemic gap at MRL 5. Achieved level 2 is assigned provisionally based on the assumption that at least two pump units were used in experiments, but this could not be confirmed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires documented mapping between simulation input parameters and experimental conditions, demonstrating that fluid properties, boundary conditions, and operating parameters used in simulations are equivalent to experimental conditions within stated measurement uncertainties.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table was prepared mapping each simulation input to the corresponding experimental measurement, including fluid viscosity (simulation: 3.5 cP; experiment: 3.48 ± 0.12 cP), density (simulation: 1050 kg/m3; experiment: 1048 ± 3 kg/m3), inlet flow rate, and rotational speed. All parameters fall within experimental measurement uncertainty bands. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou2-vad-decision",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-panel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The aggregate credibility evidence for the CFD hemolysis prediction model under VAD conditions was reviewed by the credibility assessment panel. Seven of thirteen factors were formally assessed; the remaining six were flagged as epistemic gaps. Of the seven assessed factors, two achieved their required level (Relevance of QoI at Gradation 4, Relevance of validation activities at Gradation 3, Equivalency of input parameters at Gradation 3, Test conditions at Gradation 3). Factors with shortfalls — particularly Discretization error, Numerical solver error, and Model form — were reviewed against the risk-benefit framework. The panel accepted the package on the basis that compensating controls (Monte Carlo UQ, conservative clinical threshold margin of 40% below absolute hemolysis limit) sufficiently offset the credibility gaps, and that the model will be used in conjunction with physical bench testing rather than as a standalone regulatory submission. Structured acceptance-criteria documentation was noted as incomplete for the Discretization error and Numerical solver error factors and must be remediated prior to final regulatory submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
